- VSCode Version: Code - Insiders 1.15.0-insider (ae73f8ee6f8ddb87b5e30d31655d9f55a53f4a95, 2017-07-26T07:47:53.848Z)
- OS Version: Windows_NT x64 10.0.15063

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Have the following `tasks.json`  and a tsconfig with `"compileOnSave": true`
```
{
    // See https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=733558
    // for the documentation about the tasks.json format
    "version": "2.0.0",
    "tasks": [
        {
            "type": "typescript",
            "tsconfig": "tsconfig.json",
            "watch": true,
            "problemMatcher": [
                "$tsc"
            ],
            "group": {
                "kind": "build",
                "isDefault": true
            }
        }
    ]
}
```
2. Run build task

Try to terminate task. `ctrl-shift-p -> terminate task`

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5593825/28657422-63fe0e1e-72a7-11e7-87e0-baa094aaefc1.png)


Nothing happens

- VSCode Version: Version 1.15.0-insider (1.15.0-insider)
- OS Version: Mac OS Sierra

Steps to Reproduce:

Out of the sudden an existing node js project does no longer debug. On start debugging I'm getting a request to choose the environment from a list. Choosing node.js gives an error:


```
Attribute 'program' is not absolute ('${workspaceRoot}/index.js'); consider adding '${workspaceRoot}/' as a prefix to make it absolute.

```

Launch.json was fine for the versions before and is like this:


```
{
	// Use IntelliSense to learn about possible Node.js debug attributes.
	// Hover to view descriptions of existing attributes.
	// For more information, visit: https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=830387
	"version": "0.2.0",
	"configurations": [
		
		{
			"type": "node",
			"request": "launch",
			"name": "Programm starten",
			"program": "${workspaceRoot}/index.js",
			"cwd": "${workspaceRoot}"
		},
		{
			"type": "node",
			"request": "attach",
			"name": "An den Prozess anfügen",
			"port": 5858
		}
	]
}


```

Trying to add a new debug config to no avail. 

Same does work with ordinary VSCode.

- VSCode Version: 1.14.2
- OS Version: 10.12.5

![vsc](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/50314/28625272-f96cdcdc-721b-11e7-9b7d-31f9a1b20b44.gif)

Steps to Reproduce:

* Start with code:

```javascript
try {
  start()
    .catch(err => {
      // ...
    });
```    

* Now type `}` at the end of this snippet.
* It will placed one level deep, instead of being aligned with the outer `}`:

```javascript
try {
  start()
    .catch(err => {
      // ...
    });
  }  // :-(
```

* Manually fixing the indentation level and following up with `} finally {` automatically adjusts the line again, which is frustrating.

Is it because the autoindent support doesn't understand anonymous function syntax?

Reproduces without extensions: Yes
